97":"1397","about 1430":"circa 1430","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","1438":"1438","Haroldston,Pembrokeshire,,Wales":"Haroldston St Issells, Pembrokeshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of, Cydweli, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Europe":"Europa","Cosheston, Pembroke, Wales":"Cosheston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Bodorgan, , Anglesey, Wales":"Bodorgan, Anglesey, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Before 1380–":"before 1380–Deceased","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1397–1438":"1397–1438","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1350–1438":"1350–1438","1428–Female":"1428–Deceased","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1392–1500":"1392–1500","1332–1410":"1332–1410","1342–1427":"1342–1427","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","Before 1380":"before 1380","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","about 1428":"about 1428","1500":"1500","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","Bef. 1400":"before 1400","1342":"1342","1430":"1430","1397":"1397","about 1430":"about 1430","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","1438":"1438","Haroldston,Pembrokeshire,,Wales":"Haroldston St Issells, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of, Cydweli, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Cosheston, Pembroke, Wales":"Cosheston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Bodorgan, , Anglesey, Wales":"Bodorgan, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["German: occupational name for a ferryman, Middle High German <i>verje</i>, <i>verge</i>."]}]},{"name":"Stephen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: from the personal name <i>Stephen</i>, a vernacular form of Biblical Latin <i>Stephanus</i>, Greek <i>Stephanos</i> (from Greek <i>stephanos</i> ‘crown’). The modern English form is also spelled   Steven  ; the <i>-ph-</i> spelling is due to medieval clerks' knowledge of the Biblical Latin form."],"variants":[{"name":"Santisteban","meanings":["Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Santisteban or Santesteban (from the Latin genitive form <i>Sancti Stephani</i>) for a local church or shrine dedicated to Saint Stephen (Spanish <i>San Esteban</i>); see   Stephen  . Compare   Santiesteban   and   Santistevan  ."]},{"name":"Steven","meanings":["Scottish, English, Dutch, and North German: from the personal name <i>Steven</i>, from Latin <i>Stephanus</i>, Greek <i>Stephanos</i> ‘crown’. This was a popular name throughout Christendom in the Middle Ages, having been borne by the first Christian martyr, stoned to death at Jerusalem three years after the death of Christ. In North America, this surname has also absorbed various cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Steffen  , German and Polish   Stefan  , Slovenian and Slovak <b>Štefan</b>, Hungarian <b>István</b> (see   Istvan  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see   Stevens  )."]}]},{"name":"Perrot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Gilles, Veronique.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perrotte  .","Breton: from a French-influenced pet form (see 1 above) of the personal name <i>Per</i>, Breton form of   Peter  . Compare   Perro  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pierre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Antoine, Yves, Michel, Jean Claude, Mireille, Jean Robert, Francois, Monique, Raoul, Serge.","French, Walloon, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian:","from the personal name <i>Pierre</i>, French form of   Peter   (see also below). This is one of the most frequent surnames in Haiti (along with   Jean   and   Joseph  ) and in Saint Martin. It is also established elsewhere in the West Indies (e.g. in Trinidad and Tobago, Saint Lucia, Grenada, and Bahamas)."]},{"name":"Perrotte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Damien, Henri.","Altered form of French   Perrot   or   Perrault  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>.","French: from the feminine form of   Perrot  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice ferch Stephen Perrot was born before 1380, in Haroldston St Issells, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Steven Ap Peter, was 47 and her mother, Elen Ferch John, was 37. She married Henry Malefaunt before 1400. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Before 1380–":"enne 1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1397–1438":"1397–1438","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1350–1438":"1350–1438","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1392–1500":"1392–1500","1332–1410":"1332–1410","1342–1427":"1342–1427","1385":"1385","135